# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: watchdog-supervisors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] A **brownout** is a drop in the magnitude of voltage in an electrical power system.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Unintentional brownouts can be caused by excessive electricity demand, severe weather events, or a malfunction or error affecting electrical grid control or monitoring systems.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency, or to prevent a total grid power outage due to high demand.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] The term *brownout* comes from the dimming of incandescent lighting when voltage reduces.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] In some countries, the term *brownout* refers not to a drop in voltage but to an intentional or unintentional power outage (or blackout).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Different types of electrical apparatus will react in different ways to a voltage reduction.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Some devices will be severely affected, while others may not be affected at all.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] The heat output of any resistive device, such as an electric space heater, toaster, oven, and incandescent bulbs is equal to the power consumption, which is directly proportional to the square of the applied voltage if the resistance stays constant.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Therefore, a significant reduction of heat output will occur with a relatively small reduction in voltage.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] An incandescent lamp will dim due to lower heat creation in the filament, as well as lower conversion of heat to light.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Generally speaking, no damage will occur but functionality will be impaired.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Commutated electric motors, such as universal motors, will run at reduced speed or reduced torque.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Depending on the motor design, no harm may occur.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] However, under load, the motor may draw more current due to the reduced back-EMF developed at the lower armature speed.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Unless the motor has ample cooling capacity, it may eventually overheat and burn out.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] An induction motor will draw more current to compensate for the decreased voltage, which may lead to overheating and burnout.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] If a substantial part of a grid's load is electric motors, reducing voltage may not actually reduce load and can result in damage to customers' equipment.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] An unregulated DC supply will produce a lower output voltage.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] The output voltage ripple will decrease in line with the usually reduced load current.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] In a cathode-ray tube television, the reduced output voltage will make the screen image smaller, dimmer and fuzzier.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] A switched-mode power supply will be affected if the brownout voltage is lower than the minimum input voltage of the power supply.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] As the input voltage falls, the current draw will increase to maintain the same output voltage and current, until such a point that the power supply malfunctions or its under-voltage protection kicks in and disables the output.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Brownouts can cause unexpected behavior in systems with digital control circuits.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] Reduced voltages can bring control signals below the threshold at which logic circuits can reliably detect which state is being represented.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] As the voltage returns to normal levels the logic can latch at an incorrect state; to the extent that even "can't happen" states become possible.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/brownout-electricity] The seriousness of this effect and whether steps need to be taken by the designer to prevent it depends on the nature of the equipment being controlled; for instance, a brownout may cause a motor to begin running backwards.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] In engineering, a **fail-safe** is a design feature or practice that, in the event of a failure of the design feature, inherently responds in a way that will cause minimal or no harm to other equipment, to the environment or to people.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Unlike inherent safety to a particular hazard, a system being "fail-safe" does not mean that failure is naturally inconsequential, but rather that the system's design prevents or mitigates unsafe consequences of the system's failure.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] If and when a "fail-safe" system fails, it remains at least as safe as it was before the failure.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Since many types of failure are possible, failure mode and effects analysis is used to examine failure situations and recommend safety design and procedures.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Some systems can never be made fail-safe, as continuous availability is needed.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Redundancy, fault tolerance, or contingency plans are used for these situations (e.g. multiple independently controlled and fuel-fed engines).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] As well as physical devices and systems fail-safe procedures can be created so that if a procedure is not carried out or carried out incorrectly no dangerous action results.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Fail-safe (foolproof) devices are also known as *poka-yoke* devices.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] *Poka-yoke*, a Japanese term, was coined by Shigeo Shingo, a quality expert.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] The opposite of *fail-closed* is called *fail-open*.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] Fail active operational can be installed on systems that have a high degree of redundancy so that a single failure of any part of the system can be tolerated (fail active operational) and a second failure can be detected – at which point the system will turn itself off (uncouple, fail passive).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] One way of accomplishing this is to have three identical systems installed, and a control logic which detects discrepancies.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] An example for this are many aircraft systems, among them inertial navigation systems and pitot tubes.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] During the Cold War, "failsafe point" was the term used for the point of no return for American Strategic Air Command nuclear bombers, just outside Soviet airspace.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] In the event of receiving an attack order, the bombers were required to linger at the failsafe point and wait for a second confirming order; until one was received, they would not arm their bombs or proceed further.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] The design was to prevent any single failure of the American command system causing nuclear war.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/fail-safe] This sense of the term entered the American popular lexicon with the publishing of the 1962 novel *Fail-Safe*.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] In a computer or data transmission system, a **reset** clears any pending errors or events and brings a system to normal condition or an initial state, usually in a controlled manner.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] It is usually done in response to an error condition when it is impossible or undesirable for a processing activity to proceed and all error recovery mechanisms fail.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] A computer storage program would normally perform a "reset" if a command times out and error recovery schemes like retry or abort also fail.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] A software reset (or soft reset) is initiated by the software, for example, Control-Alt-Delete key combination have been pressed, or execute restart in Microsoft Windows.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Most computers have a reset line that brings the device into the startup state and is active for a short time after powering on.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] For example, in the x86 architecture, asserting the RESET line halts the CPU; this is done after the system is switched on and before the power supply has asserted "power good" to indicate that it is ready to supply stable voltages at sufficient power levels.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Reset places less stress on the hardware than power cycling, as the power is not removed.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Many computers, especially older models, have user accessible "reset" buttons that assert the reset line to facilitate a system reboot in a way that cannot be trapped (i.e. prevented) by the operating system, or holding a combination of buttons on some mobile devices.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Devices may not have a dedicated Reset button, but have the user hold the power button to cut power, which the user can then turn the computer back on.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Out-of-band management also frequently provides the possibility to reset the remote system in this way.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Many memory-capable digital circuits (flip-flops, registers, counters and so on) accept the reset signal that sets them to the pre-determined state.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] This signal is often applied after powering on but may also be applied under other circumstances.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] After a hard reset, the register states of many hardware have been cleared.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] The ability for an electronic device to reset itself in case of error or abnormal power loss is an important aspect of embedded system design and programming.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] This ability can be observed with everyday electronics such as a television, audio equipment or the electronics of a car, which are able to function as intended again even after having lost power suddenly.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] A sudden and strange error with a device might sometimes be fixed by removing and restoring power, making the device reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Some devices, such as portable media players, very often have a dedicated reset button as they are prone to freezing or locking up.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] The lack of a proper reset ability could otherwise possibly render the device useless after a power loss or malfunction.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] User initiated hard resets can be used to reset the device if the software hangs, crashes, or is otherwise unresponsive.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] However, data may become corrupted if this occurs.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Generally, a hard reset is initiated by pressing a dedicated reset button On some systems (e.g, the PlayStation 2 video game console), pressing and releasing the power button initiates a hard reset, and holding the button turns the system off.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] The 8086 microprocessors provide RESET pin that is used to do the hardware reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] The CPU uses the values of CS and IP registers to find the location of the next instruction to execute.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] This implies that after the hardware reset, the CPU will start execution at the physical address 0xFFFF0.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] In IBM PC compatible computers, This address maps to BIOS ROM.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] The memory word at 0xFFFF0 usually contains a JMP instruction that redirects the CPU to execute the initialization code of BIOS.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] This JMP instruction is absolutely the first instruction executed after the reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Later x86 processors reset the CS and IP registers similarly, refer to Reset vector.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/reset-computing] Apple Mac computers allow various levels of resetting, including (CTL,CMD,EJECT) analogous to the three-finger salute (CTL,ALT,DEL) on Windows computers.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] A **watchdog timer** (**WDT**, or simply a **watchdog**), sometimes called a **computer operating properly timer** (**COP timer**), is an electronic or software timer that is used to detect and recover from computer malfunctions.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are widely used in computers to facilitate automatic correction of temporary hardware faults, and to prevent errant or malevolent software from disrupting system operation.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] During normal operation, the computer regularly restarts the watchdog timer to prevent it from elapsing, or *timing out*.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] If, due to a hardware fault or program error, the computer fails to restart the watchdog, the timer will elapse and generate a timeout signal.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The timeout signal is used to initiate corrective actions.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The corrective actions typically include placing the computer and associated hardware in a safe state and invoking a computer reboot.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Microcontrollers often include an integrated, on-chip watchdog.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In other computers the watchdog may reside in a nearby chip that connects directly to the CPU, or it may be located on an external expansion card in the computer's chassis.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are commonly found in embedded systems and other computer-controlled equipment where humans cannot easily access the equipment or would be unable to react to faults in a timely manner.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In such systems, the computer cannot depend on a human to invoke a reboot if it hangs; it must be self-reliant.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, remote embedded systems such as space probes are not physically accessible to human operators; these could become permanently disabled if they were unable to autonomously recover from faults.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In robots and other automated machines, a fault in the control computer could cause equipment damage or injuries before a human could react, even if the computer is easily accessed.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer is usually employed in cases like these.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are also used to monitor and limit software execution time on a normally functioning computer.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, a watchdog timer may be used when running untrusted code in a sandbox, to limit the CPU time available to the code and thus prevent some types of denial-of-service attacks.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In real-time operating systems, a watchdog timer may be used to monitor a time-critical task to ensure it completes within its maximum allotted time and, if it fails to do so, to terminate the task safely and report the failure.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The act of restarting a watchdog timer is commonly referred to as *kicking* the watchdog.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In electronic watchdogs, kicking is typically done by writing to a watchdog control port or by setting a particular bit in a register.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Alternatively, some tightly coupled watchdog timers are kicked by executing a special machine language instruction.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] An example of this is the CLRWDT (clear watchdog timer) instruction found in the instruction set of some PIC microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In computers that are running operating systems, electronic watchdog restarts are usually invoked through a device driver.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, in the Linux operating system, a user space program will kick the watchdog by interacting with the watchdog device driver, typically by writing a zero character to /dev/watchdog or by calling a KEEPALIVE ioctl.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The device driver, which serves to abstract the watchdog hardware from user space programs, may also be used to configure the time-out period and start and stop the timer.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some watchdog timers will only allow kicks during a specific time window.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The window timing is usually relative to the previous kick or, if the watchdog has not yet been kicked, to the moment the watchdog was enabled.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The window begins after a delay following the previous kick, and ends after a further delay.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] If the computer attempts to kick the watchdog before or after the window, the watchdog will not be restarted, and in some implementations this will be treated as a fault and trigger corrective action.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer is said to be *enabled* when operating and *disabled* when idle.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Upon power-up, a watchdog may be unconditionally enabled or it may be initially disabled and require an external signal to enable it.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In the latter case, the enabling signal may be automatically generated by hardware or it may be generated under software control.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] When automatically generated, the enabling signal is typically derived from the computer reset signal.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In some systems the reset signal is directly used to enable the watchdog.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In others, the reset signal is delayed so that the watchdog will become enabled at some later time following the reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] This delay allows time for the computer to boot before the watchdog is enabled.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Without this delay, the watchdog would timeout and invoke a subsequent reset before the computer can run its application software — the software which kicks the watchdog — and the system would become stuck in an endless cycle of incomplete reboots.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers come in many configurations, and many allow their configurations to be altered.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, the watchdog and CPU may share a common clock signal as shown in the block diagram below, or they may have independent clock signals or in some cases the watchdog may have no clock signal at all.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Two or more timers are sometimes cascaded to form a *multistage watchdog timer*, where each timer is referred to as a *timer stage*, or simply a *stage*.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, the block diagram below shows a three-stage watchdog.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Depending on the design, this may be implemented with multiple timers, or by emulating multiple timers with a single timer and additional logic.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In a multistage watchdog, only the first stage is kicked by the processor.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Upon first stage timeout, a corrective action is initiated and the next stage in the cascade is started.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] As each subsequent stage times out, it triggers a corrective action and starts the next stage.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Upon final stage timeout, a corrective action is initiated, but no other stage is started because the end of the cascade has been reached.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Typically, single-stage watchdog timers are used to simply restart the computer, whereas multistage watchdog timers will sequentially trigger a series of corrective actions, with the final stage triggering a computer restart.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers may have either fixed or programmable time intervals.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some watchdog timers allow the time interval to be programmed by selecting from among a few selectable, discrete values.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In others, the interval can be programmed to arbitrary values.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Typically, watchdog time intervals range from ten milliseconds to a minute or more.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In a multistage watchdog, each timer may have its own, unique time interval.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer may initiate any of several types of corrective action, including maskable interrupt, non-maskable interrupt, hardware reset, fail-safe state activation, power cycling, or combinations of these.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Depending on its architecture, the type of corrective action or actions that a watchdog can trigger may be fixed or programmable.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some computers (e.g., PC compatibles) require a pulsed signal to invoke a hardware reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In such cases, the watchdog typically triggers a hardware reset by activating an internal or external pulse generator, which in turn creates the required reset pulses.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In embedded systems and control systems, watchdog timers are often used to activate fail-safe circuitry.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] When activated, the fail-safe circuitry forces all control outputs to safe states (e.g., turns off motors, heaters, and high-voltages) to prevent injuries and equipment damage while the fault persists.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In a two-stage watchdog, the first timer is often used to activate fail-safe outputs and start the second timer stage; the second stage will reset the computer if the fault cannot be corrected before the timer elapses.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are sometimes used to trigger the recording of system state information—which may be useful during fault recovery—or debug information (which may be useful for determining the cause of the fault) onto a persistent medium.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In such cases, a second timer—which is started when the first timer elapses—is typically used to reset the computer later, after allowing sufficient time for data recording to complete.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] This allows time for the information to be saved, but ensures that the computer will be reset even if the recording process fails.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, the above diagram shows a likely configuration for a two-stage watchdog timer.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] During normal operation the computer regularly kicks Stage1 to prevent a timeout.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] If the computer fails to kick Stage1 (e.g., due to a hardware fault or programming error), Stage1 will eventually timeout.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] This event will start the Stage2 timer and, simultaneously, notify the computer (by means of a non-maskable interrupt) that a reset is imminent.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Until Stage2 times out, the computer may attempt to record state information, debug information, or both.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] As a last resort, the computer will be reset upon Stage2 timeout.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer provides automatic detection of catastrophic malfunctions that prevent the computer from kicking it.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] However, computers can have other, less-severe types of faults which do not interfere with kicking, but which still require watchdog oversight.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] To support these, a computer system is typically designed so that its watchdog timer will be kicked only if the computer deems the system functional.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The computer determines whether the system is functional by conducting one or more fault detection tests and will kick the watchdog only if all tests have passed.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In computers that are running an operating system and multiple processes, a single, simple test might be insufficient to guarantee normal operation, as it could fail to detect a subtle fault condition and consequently kick the watchdog even though a fault condition exists.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, in the case of the Linux operating system, a user-space watchdog daemon may simply kick the watchdog periodically without performing any tests.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] As long as the daemon runs normally, the system will be protected against serious system crashes such as a kernel panic.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Upon discovery of a failed test, the computer may attempt to perform a sequence of corrective actions under software control, culminating with a software-initiated reboot.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] If the software fails to invoke a reboot, the hardware watchdog timer — if available — will timeout and invoke a hardware reset.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In effect, this is a multistage watchdog timer in which the software comprises the first and the hardware WDT the final stage.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In a Linux system, for example, the watchdog daemon can be configured to attempt to perform a software-initiated reboot, which may be preferable to a hardware reset as it allows file systems to be safely unmounted and fault information to be logged prior to the reboot.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] It is essential, however, to have the insurance provided by a hardware WDT, to allow for the case in which a fault causes the daemon itself to malfunction, and thus become unable to invoke a reboot.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are implemented in various ways.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some electronic WDTs (e.g., Analog Devices MAX6324) use linear timing circuits that operate without a digital clock signal.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Other electronic WDTs, and software WDTs, typically employ digital counters as timers and rely on a clock signal for proper operation.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Electronic WDTs are usually implemented either as a stand-alone integrated circuit (IC) or as part of a more complex IC.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some stand-alone implementations contain only a WDT, whereas others bundle a WDT with other functions (e.g. supply voltage supervisors) in a common IC.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Many microcontrollers have a watchdog "module" consisting of a digital WDT and mechanisms for controlling and monitoring the WDT.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Such modules typically include related control and status registers, circuitry for qualifying restart triggers ("kicks"), and routing control logic for the timeout signal.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some microcontrollers provide an analog WDT in lieu of a digital WDT.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, Texas Instruments' TMS470 microcontroller has an analog WDT that employs an external capacitor and resistor to program the watchdog interval.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In microcontrollers and other complex digital ICs, a digital WDT is typically instantiated by synthesizing it from a description written in VHDL, Verilog or some other hardware description language.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Analog WDTs have a *kick* input and *timeout* output, but lack the clock input signal found in digital electronic watchdogs.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Circuitry and components vary widely among analog watchdogs, but in general, analog WDTs typically base their timing functions on capacitor charging rates.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, in the analog watchdog circuit shown to the right, electric current *i* gradually charges capacitor *C*, causing voltage *VC* to ramp up (rise at a constant rate).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In normal operation, periodic "kick" pulses are applied to the kick input.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Each kick causes capacitor *C* to discharge, thus restarting the voltage ramp-up.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] However, if the kicks cease or become spaced too far apart in time, *VC* will rise above the voltage comparator's threshold voltage *VTH* and, as a result, the voltage comparator will assert the *timeout* signal.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Some software watchdog timers are implemented as standard software modules.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Examples of these include "Softdog", a virtual device driver which emulates an electronic WDT and conforms to the Linux watchdog API, and MathWorks' Software Watchdog Timer, a retriggerable one-shot timer which can be instantiated by dragging its GUI representation onto a block diagram.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Other software WDTs are typically custom-designed to meet specific requirements.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Every software WDT depends on a timing reference to allow it to accurately track the passage of time.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Various mechanisms are commonly available for this purpose.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] Depending on the computer, and if used, the operating system (OS), such mechanisms may include programmable interval timers, kernel timers, the system clock, and synchronization objects (e.g., semaphores) that support timed waits.
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] For example, in bare metal applications (program running without an OS), timing references are often limited to programmable interval timers (PIT).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] In the above example, if the application program fails to kick the watchdog (by restarting the PIT), the PIT will reach the end of the watchdog interval and generate an interrupt request (IRQ).
[src:watchdog-supervisors/watchdog-timer] The associated interrupt service routine (ISR) will then execute and take corrective action via programmed I/O, system calls, or other software-controlled operations.
